      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Ans. C) Present in 3% of the population</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option C:</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Meckel diverticulum </strong>occurs as a result of <strong>failed involu­tion of the vitelline duct, </strong>which connects the<strong> lumen of the developing gut to the yolk sac</strong>. This<strong> solitary divertic­ulum extends from the antimesenteric side of the bowel.</strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\">The <strong>“rule of 2s”</strong> is often used to help remember charac­teristics of Meckel diverticula, which:</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">The <strong>prevalence of Meckel's diverticulum </strong>in the <strong>general population is 2%, </strong>not 3%, making this statement false.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><ul><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">Affects<strong> 2% of the population</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">Are generally present <strong>within 2 feet </strong>(60 cm) of the ileocecal valve</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">Are approximately <strong>2 inches</strong> (5 cm) long</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">Are <strong>twice as common in males</strong></span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">Are <strong>most often symptomatic by age 2</strong> (<i><strong>only approximately 4%</strong></i> are ever symptomatic).</span></p></li><li><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\">Has <strong>2 types</strong> of mucosa: <strong>gastric and pancreatic mucosa</strong>.</span></p></li></ul><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>The proximal part of the vitellointestinal duct</strong> is the correct embryological origin of Meckel's diverticulum.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option B.</strong>&nbsp;<strong>Symptoms of Meckel's diverticulitis</strong> may include <strong>periumbilical pain</strong>, which sometimes leads to a clinical picture resembling that of acute appendicitis.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Option D.&nbsp;Meckel's&nbsp;</strong>diverticulum is indeed located on the<strong> anti-mesenteric border of the ileum</strong>, which is the<strong> edge of the intestine </strong>that is <strong>not attached to the mesentery</strong>.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"background-color:white;color:black;font-size:12pt;\"><strong>Meckel's diverticulum </strong>is present in<strong> 2% of the population</strong>, not 3%.</span></p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\">&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt;\"><strong><u>Ref</u>: Robbins 10<sup>th</sup>/ 755</strong></span></p>",
